<sn><md>#### Horizon 

According to `SSS` (Soil Survey Staff 1962), a soil horizon may be defined as a 
&gt; `layer` of soil approximately `parallel to the soil surface`, with `characteristics` produced by ++soil forming processes++.

+++ how soil horizon are parallel to soil surface
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Pedology/Sheet.Definition/resources/soil-definition-diagram1.png)
+++

+++ soil horizon vs master horizon

A **soil horizon** is **not** the total combination of all master horizons. Instead, a **master horizon** is just a *specific type* of soil horizon.

Here is the easiest way to think about it:

* **"Soil Horizon"** is a general category name (like the word **"Vehicle"**).
* **"Master Horizon"** is a major type within that category (like a **"Truck"**).

Let's break down why:

* **A single soil horizon** is just *one* individual layer you see in the dirt. It could be a major layer (like the **A horizon**), a sub-layer (like **A1**), or a transition layer (like **Bt**).
* **Master horizons** are the six primary, big-picture building blocks (**O, A, E, B, C, R**) used to classify those individual layers.

If you combine all the master horizons together from top to bottom, you don't get a soil horizonâ€”you get a **Soil Profile** (the complete vertical cross-section of the soil).

+++
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Master horizon:
:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6 
- The `main horizons` which are `present in soil` are termed as master horizons. 
- Master or major horizons are designated by capital letters. 
  There are six master horizons. The capital letters `OAE`, `BCR` represent the master horizon of soils. 
- These `master horizons` may also be `divided into multiple horizons` which are called ++subordinate horizons++. 
  They would be referred to as `A1, A2, A3, B1, B2 and B3` respectively. 
- To designate `specific features within master horizons` or layers `lower case letters are suffixed to the capital letter` symbols viz. $\text{B}_\text{t}$, $\text{A}_\text{p}$, $\text{B}_\text{h}$, $\text{O}_\text{a}$, $\text{O}_\text{e}$, $\text{O}_\text{i}$ etc.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Pedology/Sheet.Definition/resources/soil-master-horizon-diagram.png)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Regolith:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-4
![img](https://thumbs.dreamstime.com/b/soil-structure-illustration-vertical-cross-section-surface-to-bedrock-showing-relationship-regolith-208831218.jpg)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-8 
- Regolith can be defined as `loose, unconsolidated, inorganic material of weathered rock` on which different soil forming `factors and processes interplay` to form true soil. 
- It is mainly `unconsolidated parent material`.
- It may be a `few` meters `to` `several` meters in thickness.
- The `base` of the regolith is `consolidated bed rock` (R).
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Solum:

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-9
- The solum is an `incomplete soil profile` that may be simply defined as the 
 `genetic soil` developed by `soil building forces` (Soil Survey Staff, 1975). 
- It is the `upper and most weathered part` of the soil profile. 
- In normal soils the solum includes the `A and B horizons`, or the upper part of the soil profile above the parent material.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-3
![img](https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcTI6bUnHlR0bnH_gotgAhGR-pKLALMWWI7XHf4n9xAFrWIE4tswejhGHUDN&amp;s=10)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Layer:
- A ++stratum of material++ formed either by `currency of water` or `by any geological process`. 
- It is `formed geographically`. 
- Layers are not `!parallel to the soil surface`. Layer is a `unit`. In a layer `properties are same`.
</md></sn><sn><md>:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-9
#### Soil profile
- Soil profile is a `vertical exposure` of a surficial portion of the `earth's crust` that includes 
++not only++ `all the layers` that have been `altered during the period of soil formation` 
++but also++ `deeper layers that have been influenced by pedogenesis`. 
- It can also be defined as a `vertical section` of the soil `from the surface through all the horizons` (including C horizon). 
- Soil profile represents `sequence of genetically related horizons` differentiated from one another and extended to the parent material from which the soil profile is developed.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-3
![img](https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcRAGpKsxL18vBBxFkv8qTOvva44ct2akXhRD8BbSosGFajLr5QUEZw7ivN3&amp;s=10)
:::
:::
</md></sn><sn><md>#### Pedon
:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![dgrm](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Pedology/Sheet.Definition/resources/soil-pedon-dgrm.png)
:::
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
- According to `SSS` Soil Survey Staff (1960), "a pedon is the `smallest volume` that `can be called a soil`." 
- It is `similar to a soil profile` but is `3D` three dimensional. 
- Its ++lower limit++ is the `vague` and somewhat `arbitrary limit between soil and not soil`. 
- The ++lateral dimensions++ are `large enough` to `permit study` of the nature of any horizons present, for a horizon may be variable in thickness or even discontinuous. 
- The ++shape++ of the pedon is `roughly hexagonal`. 
- Its ++area ranges++ from $1\text{ to }10\text{ m}^2$ depending on the soil variability. 
- It is a `unit` for ++soil sampling++.
:::
:::

</md></sn><sn><md>#### Polypedon

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6

- Greek word ++pedon++ means `ground`
- According to the `SSS` Soil Survey Staff (1960) defined polypedon  as 
`a natural unit` of soil that `differs from its adjoining units` on the landscape `in one or more properties` to such a degree that the `combination of all properties result` in different `responses to management`.

**Key Characteristics**
* **Physical Body:** It is a `real physical soil body`.
* **Dimensions:** It has a ++minimum area++ of more than $1\text{ km}^2$ and an `unspecified maximum area`.
* **Classification:** The polypedon are the real soil bodies that we `classify into series and higher categories`.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![img](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Nh-emon/QDoc/main/SES3/Pedology/Sheet.Definition/resources/polypedon-diagram.png)
:::
:::
</md></sn>